ce:section.ce:para:
In this study, the EDFL behavior of N:Na-CDs, with fluorescence bands in the blue region (excited at 360 nm) and the green region (excited at 440 nm), demonstrated strong potential for detecting two different metal ions. Therefore, fluorescence stability was tested under various pH, ionic concentrations, light exposure, and storage times, using the previously proposed excitation wavelengths for practical sensing applications. The fluorescence intensity of N:Na-CDs remained stable over a pH range of 5–8 under 360 and 440 nm excitations (Fig. S3a and S4a). However, the fluorescence intensity decreased under acidic (pH < 5) and alkaline (pH > 8) conditions, which might be attributed to the destruction of surface functional groups due to protonation and deprotonation [60]. This result suggests that the pH of the environment impacts the detection of metal ions. Therefore, pH 6 was used because it generates maximum fluorescence. Moreover, the fluorescence intensity of N:Na-CDs under 360 and 440 nm excitations remained almost constant, even after being maintained with various concentrations of NaCl solution (0.2–1.0
μ M
) (Fig. S3b and S4b), indicating their excellent salt resistance. In addition, the photostability of N:Na-CDs was evaluated by irradiating with a UV lamp of 365 nm for 1 h under 360 and 440 nm excitations (Fig. S3c and S4c). The fluorescence intensity remained unchanged, which suggests that N:Na-CDs show favorable photobleaching resistance. Furthermore, the fluorescence intensity of N:Na-CDs under 360 and 440 nm excitations showed almost no change after 30 days of storage (Fig. S3d and S4d), demonstrating their remarkable photostability. All these results confirm that N:Na-CDs possess great potency for fluorescence sensing applications under various environmental conditions.

Based on the previous discussion, we used the EDFL behavior of N:Na-CDs, with fluorescence bands in the blue region (excited at 360 nm) and the green region (excited at 440 nm) to investigate excitation-dependent selective detection of metal ions. As shown in Fig. 4a, the fluorescence intensity of N:Na-CDs was substantially quenched up to 55 % by adding Fe3+ under 360 nm excitation. In contrast, other metal ions (Zn2+, Cu2+, Ni2+, Co2+, Li+, Al3+, and Ag+) caused negligible changes in fluorescence intensity under the same testing conditions (1000
μ M
), demonstrating the excellent specificity of N:Na-CDs for Fe3+ detection under 360 nm excitation. Moreover, the fluorescence emission spectra of N:Na-CDs and various metal ions were recorded under 440 nm excitation, as delineated in Fig. 4b. The fluorescence intensity of N:Na-CDs showed no significant change after the addition of Zn2+, Cu2+, Ni2+, Co2+, Li+, and Al3+. Additionally, a minor quenching of around 18 % was recorded in the presence of Fe3+, which could be attributed to potential complex formation between N:Na-CDs and Fe3+; however, this effect was insignificant. Notably, the fluorescence intensity showed a significant quenching up to 56 % in adding Ag+, demonstrating their outstanding selectivity for Ag+ detection under 440 nm excitation. Furthermore, the anti-interference study was investigated to illustrate N:Na-CDs' selectivity for Fe3+ and Ag+ detection under 360 and 440 nm excitations (see Fig. 4c and d). The presence of competing metal ions had no significant impact on detecting Fe3+ under 360 nm excitation. Similarly, Ag+ detection remained unaffected by other competing ions under 440 nm excitation. These results confirm that the excitation-dependent selective detection of Fe3+ and Ag+ can be effectively achieved using the EDFL behavior of N:Na-CDs. In addition, the high selectivity and anti-interference performance of N:Na-CDs as fluorescence sensors for Fe3+ and Ag+ can be attributed to the specific interactions between these metal ions and the O- and N-containing groups on the N:Na-CDs' surfaces, which respond to different excitation wavelengths [24,61].
